Wave-5 cirrus5 capture (/tmp/cirrus5/SDLDBG.LOG line 86):

  sw-present-timing block @present=200:
    queue_flush_ms_avg=323.199  render_present_ms_avg=9.561  total=332.761

After patch 0047 (Approach C: pre-convert sprites to RGB565) the
queue_flush is still 323 ms across 340 drawcalls = ~0.95 ms per call.
Approach C eliminated the per-pixel format conversion in the SW
renderer's BlitSurface, but SDL3's per-call validation + dispatch +
queue allocation remain fixed costs that don't shrink as pixel work
shrinks. SDL_RenderTexture has fundamental overhead independent of the
work it does.

Approach B: bypass SDL_RenderTexture for the dominant 16×16 case by
writing directly to the SDL_Window surface (which IS the SW renderer's
backbuffer — verified by reading SDL_render_sw.c §60-80).

Integration strategy chosen: write directly to window->surface via
SDL_GetWindowSurface. Verified safe by tracing SW_ActivateRenderer
in vendor/SDL/src/render/software/SDL_render_sw.c:

    static SDL_Surface *SW_ActivateRenderer(SDL_Renderer *renderer)
    {
        SW_RenderData *data = (SW_RenderData *)renderer->internal;
        if (!data->surface) {
            data->surface = data->window;
        }
        if (!data->surface) {
            SDL_Surface *surface = SDL_GetWindowSurface(renderer->window);
            if (surface) {
                data->surface = data->window = surface;
            }
        }
        return data->surface;
    }

`data->surface` (the SW renderer's draw target) is set from
SDL_GetWindowSurface(window). Therefore writes to window->surface from
our fast path land on exactly the same memory the SW renderer would
write to via SDL_RenderTexture. SDL_RenderPresent (= SW_RenderPresent
→ SDL_UpdateWindowSurface → DOS backend's UpdateWindowFramebuffer)
copies window->surface to VRAM. All paths converge at window->surface.
No need to expose SDL3 internals via texture->internal or replace the
present pipeline.

Implementation
--------------

Surface class (Surface.{h,cpp}):
  - retain the RGB565 SDL_Surface created in patch 0047 (was destroyed
    immediately after texture creation; now kept for the lifetime of
    the Surface).
  - new accessors: surface16bpp(), colorkey16(), hasColorkey().
  - cleanup() frees both the texture and the surface — they live and
    die together so the surface16bpp() != NULL check is sufficient as a
    fast-path opt-in.
  - colorkey is pre-extracted to a Uint16 at load time so the inner loop
    avoids SDL_GetSurfaceColorKey calls.

Renderer::drawSurface (Renderer.cpp):
  - new helper _try_fast_blit_16x16 attempts the fast path first.
    Conditions: src->surface16bpp() != NULL, alpha == 255, srcrect 16×16,
    dstrect 16×16 (no scale), window surface format == RGB565, window
    surface dims == 320×240 (no logical-presentation letterbox).
  - on Cirrus + PIN_WINDOW_TO_NATIVE the window surface is exactly
    320×240 RGB565 → fast path engages. On Mach64 with 640×480 window
    and 320×240 logical presentation, the fast path falls through and
    the existing SDL_RenderTexture path remains correct.
  - SDL_FlushRenderer is called inside the fast path BEFORE the direct
    write so any pending slow-path commands (font, mirrored sprites,
    spot_light) drain to window->surface first. Z-order = call-order is
    preserved. When the queue is empty (the common steady-state case
    after a sequence of fast-path calls), FlushRenderCommands early-
    returns at SDL_render.c §343 — essentially free.
  - Inner loop: 16×16 RGB565 with colorkey skip, or per-row SDL_memcpy
    when no colorkey.
  - Edge clipping: dst may legitimately be slightly off-screen for
    sprites near playfield boundaries (logged as `(-8,-8)` etc in
    wave-5 drawcall traces). Clip to win bounds before the loop;
    wholly-off-screen returns success with no work.
  - new fastpath_audit log line at the per-100-flip cadence reports
    taken/skipped counts so the lever 2 win shows up alongside the
    drawcall and alpha-mod audits.

Verified under DOSBox-X (cycles=max via --fast smoke):

  fastpath audit block 1: taken=40883 skipped=413 pct_x10=989
  ... title scene runs at 98.9% fast-path hit rate.
  fastpath audit block 6: taken=100 skipped=2500 pct_x10=38
  ... transitional scene with mostly font/dialogue (slow-path expected)
  fastpath audit block 9: taken=15462 skipped=1158 pct_x10=930
  ... main menu screen back to ~93% hit rate

Title scene + post-title intro scene + main menu all render visually
correctly: sprites, tiles, fonts, layering, colors all preserved.
Mirrored sprites, font glyphs, and spot_light render through the slow
path naturally.

Why DOS needs this
------------------

SDL3's renderer per-call overhead (~0.95 ms on real Cirrus per the
wave-5 capture) exists regardless of the renderer backend. The SW
renderer is the only option on DOS (no GPU). Approach C (patch 0047)
already eliminated the per-pixel cost; Approach B eliminates the
per-call cost for the dominant case. Together they target ~50 µs per
drawcall (the actual blit work), reducing 340-drawcall queue_flush
from 323 ms → ~17 ms target on real HW.

Architectural note: the fast path's correctness depends on the
SW renderer NOT using a separate backbuffer (verified per
SW_ActivateRenderer above). If a future SDL3 release refactors the SW
renderer to keep its own surface separate from window->surface, this
patch would silently render to the wrong target. The conservative
defense would be to write ALL drawcalls (not just 16×16) directly to
window->surface and disable SDL_UpdateWindowSurface's renderer path
entirely — out of scope for wave 6 but documented here as the next
step if the assumption breaks.

Local-only patch per workspace policy (memory note "SDL upstream —
local patches only"): never PR'd upstream. The equivalent change to
SDL3 itself would be upstream-PR territory.

